@node introduction "cha_stanley.guide/Introduction"

	Stanley is a tool for cutting up samples (often breakbeats)
	into small sections quickly and easily.  The program is a
	plug-in for OctaMED SoundStudio, using ARexx.

	Before stanley, to cut up a breakbeat you would have to range
	each individual drum beat (perhaps using loop points to store
	the other end of the beat as you zoom in to select the other),
	copy it and paste it to another sample.

	Stanley automates this process: you specify the starts of the
	beats and it chops out the beats and stores them in separate
	samples.  I'm not very good at explaining - try it, its quite
	simple.

 	Stanley can enter the note data corresponding to the rhythm of
 	the original breakbeat, to timing-pulse accuracy in hires mode.
 	This means that you can replace the break by note data, and edit
 	it conveniently.

@endnode

@node usage "cha_stanley.guide/Usage"

	Stanley opens a window on the OctaMED screen.  The left half
	contains a lists of all the marker points, on the right are
	the controls for manipulating the markers.  Only limited actions
	can be performed on the start and end markers.

	Close   The close gadget of the window exits stanley.

	Add     Add a marker at the start of the range marked in the
	        sample editor window.  Only one marker can be set at
	        any point.

	Delete  Deletes the current marker point from the list.  Useful
	        if you made a mistake, but there is no undo feature.

	Range   Marks a range from the current marker to the next marker
	        in the sample editor.

	Play    Plays the sample from the current marker to the next
	        marker.

	To      If the check box is not ticked, stanley uses an automatic
	        method for choosing the destination:  the markers are
	        stored in order in the free samples following the source
	        sample (so no samples are overwritten).  This is the
	        default mode.

	        If the check box is ticked, you can select a destination
	        sample for the current marker.  The sample already there
	        will be overwritten, so be careful.

	Name    The name of the current marker.  This is shown alongside
	        the offset and destination sample in the list, and is also
	        copied to the name of the destination sample.  Defaults to
	        the name of the source sample.

	Stanley This button does the hard work:  until you press this
	        button nothing is changed.  This button cuts up the
	        sample into pieces and pastes them to the destination.
	        The default pitch, finetune, transpose and volume settings
	        are copied from the source instrument.

	        WARNING: Stanley does no checking on destinations, so if one
	                 part is copied to the source then "bad things" might
	                 happen.  The auto mode is safe, but "bad things"
	                 might happen if there are not enough free instruments
	                 slots after the source.

	                 I haven't checked what the "bad things" are, but it
	                 probably results in copying bits of sample over
	                 samples that shouldn't be modified.

 	Notify  Generates note data for the cut up samples to play the
 	        original rhythm.  All notes are inserted at the default
 	        pitch, so set this before using stanley.  The notes are
 	        put into the first track of the range marked in the tracker
 	        editor.  A warning will appear if the range is not long
 	        enough for all the notes to fit properly.

	        If the default pitch is not specified, C-3 is used.

 	        You must use the stanley button before using notify.

 	Hires   If the check box is ticked (default), then notify will use
 	        command 1Fx0 for more accurate translation.  Commands are
 	        inserted into the current command page.

 |	        If the check box is not ticked, then notify will use no
 |	        commands, and just put notes on the nearest line.
 |
 |	Reset   Clears all markers, and sets the current sample as the
 |	        source.  New end markers are added.
 |
 |	Load    Load marker positions from a .stanley file.  Currently all
 |	        the markers are replaced, so be careful.  Only marker
 |	        positions are loaded, and not the destination instrument
 |	        numbers or names.
 |
 |	        WARNING: very little checking is performed on the
 |	                 file format, so be careful - make sure you
 |	                 are reading from a genuine .stanley file.
 |
 |	Save    Save marker positions to a .stanley file.  Only the marker
 |	        positions are saved, and not the destination instrument
 |	        numbers or names.

@endnode

